1. The Graph Laplacian — the “vibration detector” of networks

Any system that can be represented as a network can be analyzed spectrally.

Nodes = things
Edges = relationships

From that graph we build the Laplacian matrix:

L = D - A

Where:
	•	A = adjacency matrix (connections)
	•	D = degree matrix (number of connections)

The eigenvalues of L reveal the vibration modes of the network.

Interpretation:

Eigenvalue feature	Meaning
smallest eigenvalue	connectivity baseline
second eigenvalue (Fiedler value)	structural bottlenecks
large eigenvalues	tightly bound clusters

So the graph has resonance frequencies just like a drum.

